s education, her letters to other learned women, and her own account of her early life, as well as responses to her work from male contemporaries, and rare writings by Schurman's mentor, Voetius. This volume will interest the general reader as well as students of women's, religious, and social history.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aChristian women. 0aEducation. 0aReformed Church. 0aReligion. 0aSocial sciences. 0aWomen in Christianity. 0aWomen in the Reformed Church. 0aWomen. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aIrwin, Joyce L.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226850009423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226850009.jpg  a978-3-11-066785-1  UChP eBook-Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles